### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

core

### Is this a regression?

No

### Description

Component: 

```typescript
class Component {
    public readonly id = input.required<string>();

    constructor() {
        afterNextRender(() => {
             console.log(this.id());
        });
    }
}
```

Test:

```typescript
const fixture = TestBed.createComponent(Component); // Error Input is required but no value is available yet.

fixture.componentRef.setInput('id', 'test');
```

### Please provide a link to a minimal reproduction of the bug

_No response_

### Please provide the exception or error you saw

```true
Input is required but no value is available yet.
```

### Please provide the environment you discovered this bug in (run `ng version`)

```true
19.1.4
```

### Anything else?

Workaround:

```typescript
class Component {
    public readonly id = input.required<string>();

    constructor() {
        const effectRef = effect(() => {
             console.log(this.id());
             effectRef.destroy();
        });
    }
}
```

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

For a simple request w/ one signal, the loader won't fetch when the signal is undefined. Now imagine a resource that requires multiple parameters.  What happens in the case of combining multiple signals for a request?
```ts
signal0 = input<string>();
signal1 = input<string>();

resource({
  loader: ({ request }) => this._service.get(request.arg0, request.arg1),
  request: () => ({ arg0: signal0(), arg1: signal1() }),
})
```
Regardless of whether one or both signals are undefined the loader still fetches, resulting in a flaky failure or something unexpected. There's a way to overcome this but you need to be aware of it and it'll quickly become unwieldy the more parameters there are.
```ts
signal0 = input<string>();
signal1 = input<string>();

resource({
  loader: ({ request }) => this._service.get(request.arg0, request.arg1),
  request: () =>
    signal0() === undefined || signal1() === undefined
      ? undefined
      : { arg0: signal0(), arg1: signal1() },
});
```
This results in the expected behavior matching the one signal example.

### Proposed solution

RxJS features a possible solution with this pattern:
```ts
combineLatest([observable0, observable1]).pipe(
  switchMap(([arg0, arg1]) => this._service.get(arg0, arg1)),
);
combineLatest({ observable0, observable1 }).pipe(
  switchMap(({ observable0, observable1 }) =>
    this._service.get(observable0, observable1),
  ),
);
```
The reactive function could automatically combine signal objects or arrays in the same matter, waiting for all of their values to become available.

### Alternatives considered

Should this behavior be opt-in instead? Give it its own reactive function separate from request.

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

I try to create some utility functions for angular signals (SignalNode, ComputedNode). This nodes can have value: UNSET | COMPUTING | ERRORED. But I can't check this, because I can't import this symbols diurectly.

### Proposed solution

Export UNSET, COMPUTING, ERRORED from core/primitives/signals.
Or add public utility functions to check this.

### Alternatives considered

```typescript
function isSymbol(value: unknown, description: string): value is symbol {
	return (
		typeof value === 'symbol' && String(value) === `Symbol(${description})`
	);
}

function importSymbols() {
	const s = computed(() => {
		throw new Error();
	});

	const node = s[SIGNAL] as ComputedNode<symbol>;

	let { value } = node;

	const UNSET = isSymbol(value, 'UNSET') ? value : null;
	let COMPUTING: symbol | null = null;
	let ERRORED: symbol | null = null;

	Object.defineProperty(node, 'value', {
		get(): any {
			return value;
		},
		set(v: any) {
			value = v;

			if (isSymbol(value, 'COMPUTING')) {
				COMPUTING = value;
			}
			if (isSymbol(value, 'ERRORED')) {
				ERRORED = value;
			}
		},
	});

	producerUpdateValueVersion(node);

	if (!UNSET || !COMPUTING || !ERRORED) {
		throw new Error('Could not import symbols');
	}

	return { UNSET, COMPUTING, ERRORED };
}
```

### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

localize

### Is this a regression?

No

### Description

I have a `LoginService` like this, and when the backend returns an error, I need to throw different errors based on the responses from the backend, a simplified version of my service is as followed

```ts
@Injectable()
export class LoginService {
  private readonly _httpClient = inject(HttpClient);

  async logInWithEmailPassword(payload: { email: string; password: string; }) {
    const responseBody = await firstValueFrom(
      this._httpClient
        .post<ResponseBody<AuthenticatedUser>>('/api/login`, payload)
        .pipe(
          catchError(error => {
            throw new Error(this._resolveEmailLoginErrorMessage(error.info));
          })
        )
    );
  }

  private _resolveEmailLoginErrorMessage(errorInfo) {
    const errorInfoPayload = errorInfo.payload;

    if (errorInfoPayload.code === ExceptionCode.INCORRECT_EMAIL_OR_PASSWORD) {
      return $localize`Email or password was incorrect.`
    } else if (errorInfoPayload.code === ExceptionCode.USER_IS_BLOCKED) {
      return $localize`Your account has been blocked. Please contact the administrator to restore access.`;
    }

    return $localize`Something went wrong`
  }
}
```

When I localize my application with `LoginService` implemented exactly like above, the strings in `_resolveEmailLoginErrorMessage` method aren't being picked up by the localization engine. **However**, when I move `_resolveEmailLoginErrorMessage` to a different file that will be imported by `LoginService`, then those strings will be added to the messages file as expected.

Is there anything that I can do so that strings in a service are picked up by the localization engine?

